The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, VSCHT (Chemical-Technology University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way for dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances described as metalokarborans act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus reproduction in a different way from all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come to new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding on the virus protein.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-faceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
