The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived in today's New Mexico about 215 million years ago, which was on the equator in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangäa.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other palaeontologists began digging at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for Trias deposits, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as new species.
During the excavation, they carried together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the Sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosauric fossils from the trias are extremely rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
Especially spectacular is this find not, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current teaching opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur-Dinos is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the ankles split into their three main development lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, which were known as "long heels" of four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plants refreshing Ornithischia (Vogelbassauriers), among which were, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosau.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On Tawa hallae’s skull, for example, the researchers found evidence of airbags as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive Theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
As the related line of the huge Sauropods later also owned air bags and lightweight construction bones, probably already the common ancestor of both groups had produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs in South America have lived so far, the researchers follow that the ankles appeared there for the first time.
Thus, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America over all parts of the earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass as Supercontinent Pangäa.
The fact is that together with Tawa hallae, the team found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot derive from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner from the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
There are, of course, contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonn's palaeontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be distorted, because in South America just a lot of primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile strain to the ruling agricultural vertebrates of the earth’s Middle Ages, is still puzzling.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the saurs of flight and with numerous other axes.
Towards the end of the trias, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relationship on the border from the Trias to the Jura died.
Success Story Has Not Endured Forever
