Support for brake maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-blocking braking system at that time, and just as the ESP stability control system is doing, the emergency braking aid systems have to become a compulsory equipment in the European cars.
In fact, they are already required for all newly approved passenger cars and light small hauliers, for the remaining vehicles a time limit was set until the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of the walkers, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents due to their working methods.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake maneuver, which recognizes the system on the brake pedal based on the brake strength performed by the driver.
However, this system does not exercise this pressure until the end.
According to a survey commissioned by the component manufacturer for Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to step onto the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, enters the brake system with maximum force and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the brake distance which a car returns during the braking process.
According to a study conducted by the EU, up to 1,100 fatal accidents that damage Fußgangers could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistants.
There would be even fewer accidents - one expects that every fourth accident with personal damage could be prevented - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects (by radar or camera) obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant exercises the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to minimise the damage.
